Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.353
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:08.630 --> 00:00:12.530
SPEAKER 1: Standing next
to me is Winifred Reilly.

00:00:12.530 --> 00:00:16.010
She is a psychotherapist
specializing in marital therapy

00:00:16.010 --> 00:00:19.860
and relationship issues in a
private practice in Berkeley,

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:21.200
California.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:24.110
In her 35 years of
clinical practice,

00:00:24.110 --> 00:00:26.570
she has treated
hundreds of couples,

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:29.810
many who are convinced
they're headed for divorce.

00:00:29.810 --> 00:00:32.060
Ms. Reilly has been a
guest lecturer on marriage

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:33.950
and sexuality, and
her writing has

00:00:33.950 --> 00:00:36.680
appeared on the "Huffington
Post", "The Good Men

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:41.030
Project", "XO Jane," and her
blog, "Speak of Marriage".

00:00:41.030 --> 00:00:44.210
I'm so excited that we get
to hear Winifred Reilly.

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:44.990
Thanks.

00:00:44.990 --> 00:00:47.702
WINIFRED REILLY:
Thank you so much.

00:00:47.702 --> 00:00:49.160
So I'm going to
start first-- thank

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:50.243
you so much for having me.

00:00:50.243 --> 00:00:52.310
I'm going to start
first by telling you

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:54.320
this personal story.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:58.700
So my husband and I were married
early on a Sunday morning.

00:00:58.700 --> 00:01:02.450
By late that afternoon, we were
in the car driving down 101

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:05.450
to spend a few days
down in Big Sur.

00:01:05.450 --> 00:01:07.610
So our friends had
painted Just Married

00:01:07.610 --> 00:01:09.470
across the back of our car.

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:11.310
So as we're driving
along, people

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:15.120
are honking, and waving,
and giving the thumbs up.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:16.910
And then this guy
in a pick up truck

00:01:16.910 --> 00:01:19.880
comes pulling on up to our car.

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:23.630
And he's honking for my husband
to roll down the window.

00:01:23.630 --> 00:01:26.630
And then at about
75 miles an hour,

00:01:26.630 --> 00:01:29.450
this guy leans across
the cab of his truck

00:01:29.450 --> 00:01:34.410
and yells out the
window, don't do it.

00:01:34.410 --> 00:01:37.050
So I'm married, what?

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:39.870
Maybe five hours, six hours.

00:01:39.870 --> 00:01:42.190
And I'm thinking, nah.

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:44.050
That'll never be us.

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:47.520
Not the business of yelling out
of the car window at newlyweds,

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.260
but the idea that we would
be disgruntled or unhappy.

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:53.760
It never occurred to me.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:56.640
Now, you'd think that I
would have known better given

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.832
my work, given that I'm a
marriage and family therapist.

00:01:59.832 --> 00:02:02.040
I mean, you'd think I would
have been better prepared

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:05.190
in some way for what
marriage would be.

00:02:05.190 --> 00:02:08.160
But actually, I was just
as naive and unprepared

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:09.240
as my clients.

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:12.890
I had ideas that
were fairly useless,

00:02:12.890 --> 00:02:16.980
like we have so much in
common and we're so in love.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:19.200
How hard could this be?

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:21.360
So here's what a
client of mine said

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.491
on the eve of her
third anniversary.

00:02:24.491 --> 00:02:24.990
Yeah.

00:02:24.990 --> 00:02:26.420
I know marriage takes work.

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:27.780
Everybody knows that.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:31.500
I was prepared for that, and I
knew we have our difficulties.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:34.950
But I never, ever imagined
that the biggest difficulty

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:38.420
in my life would be
my husband, George.

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:42.050
So I'm here today to talk
about my book, "It Takes One

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:43.550
to Tango".

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:46.550
I'm going to talk about
why marriage is hard,

00:02:46.550 --> 00:02:49.400
and I'm going to
tell you a little bit

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:52.340
of my personal
story, how I changed

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:55.520
my own marriage by
taking a leadership role,

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:59.540
and how you can create a
vibrant and satisfying loving

00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:01.320
relationship too.

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:07.610
So the question is, why
is marriage so hard?

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:09.220
Well, here.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:12.520
Marriage puts two people
into a small space

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:15.790
with the expectation of keeping
them there for a lifetime.

00:03:15.790 --> 00:03:18.100
And then says, good luck.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:21.880
Marriage doesn't come with
a guide book or a road map.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:25.690
And none of us come in with
all the skills that we need.

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:28.090
Many of us have had
terrible role models.

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:31.550
We've had parents who fought to
the death or hated each other

00:03:31.550 --> 00:03:33.390
and finally divorced.

00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:38.290
Or we had over-idealized
romantic role models,

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:41.530
like grandparents who
were married 75 years

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:44.756
and swore they'd never
had one, single argument.

00:03:44.756 --> 00:03:46.630
Now, and then there you
are on your honeymoon

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:49.370
on the third day, and you're
ready to kill each other.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:52.000
So you've completely blown
it right out of the gate.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.050
Then we also have
mistaken ideas,

00:03:56.050 --> 00:04:01.120
like marriage shouldn't be
hard, or people who fight

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:02.860
should get a divorce.

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:07.340
Or those people look really
happy, what's wrong with us?

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.540
You know, so we have the
negative role models.

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:13.820
There's a confusion
about the difference

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:16.899
between marriage and courtship.

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:20.230
Courtship is that wonderful
drunk on love beginning

00:04:20.230 --> 00:04:24.370
phase where it's all about
sameness and loveliness.

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:26.710
And you just can't
believe that you finally

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:30.580
found someone so perfect,
someone so much like you

00:04:30.580 --> 00:04:32.530
with so much in common.

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:36.160
And unfortunately,
courtship doesn't last.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:40.630
And many people really do think
that's what relationships are.

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:44.380
So when courtship ends, they
just move on to the next one.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:47.830
Or when marriage gets difficult
or the long the longer

00:04:47.830 --> 00:04:52.180
relationships start to
struggle, people think, nah.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:55.490
I'd better move on.

00:04:55.490 --> 00:04:59.340
So when people struggle and they
find marriage to be difficult,

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:03.370
what I want people to know
is that nothing is wrong.

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:06.180
It's just that marriage
is a really tough teacher

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:09.280
and we all have plenty to learn.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:12.780
But many of us don't like
the idea of being beginners.

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:14.610
We think, somehow,
we're supposed

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:19.810
to be good at everything, even
without any practice at all.

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:24.520
Now, my graduate school training
mimicked some of these myths

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:28.570
about marriage that were
not particularly helpful.

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:31.300
But worse, it seemed
to make the trouble

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:33.520
that people had in
marriage be more

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:38.470
of a pathology, sort of an
aberration, more than the norm.

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:42.100
But I was thinking, there
are some really lovely people

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:43.540
that I see in my practice.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:46.840
And my husband and I,
were not actually crazy,

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:50.180
but we were going at it in
ways that didn't make sense.

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:54.230
So I thought, something
is wrong with this idea.

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:57.010
So I decided to figure out why.

00:05:57.010 --> 00:06:00.310
And in order to do that,
I decided to turn myself

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.810
into a marriage expert.

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:06.020
Now, back then, none
of this existed.

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:07.613
I couldn't just
sit at my computer.

00:06:07.613 --> 00:06:11.270
Well, actually, I didn't even
have a computer back then.

00:06:11.270 --> 00:06:13.460
And I couldn't just
sit down and Google

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:15.970
why is my husband
driving me crazy?

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:17.092
What am I supposed to do?

00:06:17.092 --> 00:06:18.050
There was none of that.

00:06:18.050 --> 00:06:19.910
So I went to the bookstore.

00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:24.170
You know, I read books, and I
took workshops and trainings,

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:26.250
and went to conferences.

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:30.320
And here's the most
interesting thing that I found.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:34.340
It pretty much turned everything
I understood about marriage

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:37.930
and relationships upside down.

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:40.180
So most of us
think that marriage

00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:42.850
is about agreement
and consensus,

00:06:42.850 --> 00:06:47.410
about compromising,
and meeting halfway.

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:51.400
It's our need for consensus
that's driving us crazy.

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:54.580
We need this agreement,
we need this validation.

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:56.470
We need somebody to say, yes.

00:06:56.470 --> 00:06:57.170
I hear you.

00:06:57.170 --> 00:06:58.030
I agree with you.

00:06:58.030 --> 00:06:59.590
I perfectly understand you.

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:00.100
Oh, yes.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:02.800
What you're saying makes
perfect sense, and yes.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:04.460
Let's do it your way.

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:07.900
But, of course, you know, of
course we'd all like that.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.620
I mean, everybody
wants validation.

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:13.360
You know what I like to
say is that validation

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:16.720
is a perfectly
fine thing to want

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:20.770
and it's a really
dangerous thing to need.

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:24.310
So here's essentially
what it comes down to.

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:29.380
We need to learn how
to disagree, not agree.

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:32.260
Now, I'm not saying that we
have to fight all the time

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.360
and that that's the
key to happiness.

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:36.670
I'm just saying that
what we have to do

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:40.330
is we need to learn to
effectively deal with being

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:42.830
two different people.

00:07:42.830 --> 00:07:45.850
This was 180 degrees
off of everything

00:07:45.850 --> 00:07:49.450
that I believed up until
then, but somehow it

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:51.050
made perfect sense to me.

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:53.680
I didn't know how to
apply it to my life,

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:56.890
but I knew that I
was onto something.

00:07:56.890 --> 00:08:00.550
So let's consider this
quote from Einstein.

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:04.330
"Central to the advancement
of human civilization

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:06.700
is the spirit of open inquiry.

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:09.880
We must not only learned to
tolerate our differences--

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:14.290
we must welcome them as the
richness and diversity which

00:08:14.290 --> 00:08:18.930
can lead to true intelligence."

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:23.310
So I read this quote, and I'm
in a workshop for therapists.

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:26.610
And we're working with
how to deal with our most

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:29.850
impossible, difficult couples.

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:32.610
So I thought immediately
of this couple

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:34.260
I'll call Bruce and Cindy.

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:37.190
They were my couple from hell.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:41.120
They fought about everything.

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:43.250
They'd get to the corner
and they couldn't decide--

00:08:43.250 --> 00:08:45.499
you know, if they're just
taking a walk-- whether they

00:08:45.499 --> 00:08:47.390
should go right or left.

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:52.640
So I tried to imagine
die-hard vegan Bruce welcoming

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:55.670
as rich and diverse his
wife Cindy's interest

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:58.730
in eating hamburger, when
this guy would not even

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:01.070
wear leather shoes.

00:09:01.070 --> 00:09:03.950
And what I realized
is that's the point.

00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:05.710
We don't have to get--

00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:08.180
Bruce and Cindy are never
going to agree on anything.

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:11.870
And the good news is,
we didn't actually

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:14.330
have to make them agree.

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:19.700
But here's one of the pieces
of trouble with consensus.

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:20.530
OK.

00:09:20.530 --> 00:09:24.940
So have you ever noticed that
your version and your spouse's

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:27.730
version sound nothing alike?

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:29.620
Have you ever thought
that maybe you're

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:33.400
living in alternate
realities, parallel realities

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:35.240
on a good day?

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:39.280
So here's how I observed
this in my office.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.980
Somebody is there and
they're starting to talk.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.310
And they say, you know,
and this thing happened,

00:09:44.310 --> 00:09:45.310
and that thing happened.

00:09:45.310 --> 00:09:48.730
And then their partner moves
like, some micro-movement,

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:50.650
a little eyebrow, a little--

00:09:50.650 --> 00:09:51.220
[SNIFFING]

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:51.970
Something happens.

00:09:51.970 --> 00:09:52.690
And, what?

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:53.189
What?

00:09:53.189 --> 00:09:54.820
And they're completely riveted.

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:56.770
They can't finish a sentence.

00:09:56.770 --> 00:09:59.050
They can't complete a thought.

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:00.430
And they say, see?

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:01.630
This is what I mean.

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:06.390
We can't talk about X. I'm
not allowed to bring up Y.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:09.400
And I say, why not?

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:12.200
Who made these rules?

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.620
And so if you want to
know who made these rules,

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:17.920
I'm going to ask you
to take a minute,

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:22.900
and I want you to think
about, imagine and remember,

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:27.490
the two of you back in the
early days of your relationship.

00:10:27.490 --> 00:10:28.510
There you are.

00:10:28.510 --> 00:10:31.560
You're in Starbucks
sharing cafe lattes.

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:35.380
Maybe you're actually drinking
one tea with two straws.

00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:38.830
And you're planning your
weekend away, romantic.

00:10:38.830 --> 00:10:41.020
The first trip to the country.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:44.740
And now meanwhile, in
some smoky back room,

00:10:44.740 --> 00:10:47.290
your people and your
partner's people

00:10:47.290 --> 00:10:51.330
are back there negotiating the
terms of your relationship.

00:10:51.330 --> 00:10:51.890
OK.

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:52.740
Fine.

00:10:52.740 --> 00:10:55.550
I won't question
how many times a day

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:57.031
she has to talk to her mother.

00:10:57.031 --> 00:10:57.530
OK.

00:10:57.530 --> 00:10:58.030
Fine.

00:10:58.030 --> 00:10:59.660
And she's just not
going to bring up

00:10:59.660 --> 00:11:02.140
what the cost of
those club-level seats

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:03.300
are at the ball park.

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:05.760
And all right, really?

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:06.260
OK.

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:09.630
They'll never, ever,
ever talk about sex.

00:11:09.630 --> 00:11:12.000
So this gets signed into law.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.800
They shake hands, Meanwhile,
you're out there having a lark.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:20.120
You have no idea that these
are actually the rules that

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:21.620
will confine you.

00:11:21.620 --> 00:11:23.630
They will define you.

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:25.490
They will make you miserable.

00:11:25.490 --> 00:11:28.250
They will make you feel like
you are living in a box,

00:11:28.250 --> 00:11:33.750
until you have the strength
and stamina to change them.

00:11:33.750 --> 00:11:37.160
Now, [INAUDIBLE]
about courtship, about

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:41.780
courtship being about all
things lovely and wonderful.

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:45.680
These rules, you made these
rules back in the beginning

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:50.240
when the goal was to keep
the peace, to fall in love,

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:54.920
to preserve your bond, to
keep your partner essentially

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:56.900
from thinking you're
completely awful

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:58.640
and deciding to leave you.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:01.040
So all of these
things are hidden,

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:05.360
but you make these rules and
you will have to live with them.

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:08.450
So that's what courtship is.

00:12:08.450 --> 00:12:10.910
And so here is marriage.

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:16.550
Marriage is essentially about
the rest of your life together.

00:12:16.550 --> 00:12:21.050
You can't keep up the
facade of not being yourself

00:12:21.050 --> 00:12:24.280
when you're in a
long relationship.

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:27.800
So marriage is really about
coming to terms with the fact

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.590
that you are two different
people, that you want

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:33.980
different things, that
you like different things,

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:36.530
that some of the things
you're going to want

00:12:36.530 --> 00:12:41.190
are going to clash with what
your partner has in mind.

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:44.790
Now, this is really,
really important.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:47.300
We have to figure out
how to deal with this,

00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:49.910
our differences, with grace.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:52.160
And in order to do
this, you're going

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:56.160
to have to learn how
to stand on your own.

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:57.260
This is crucial.

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:00.020
This is the whole
point that I wrote--

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:02.570
this is why I wrote this book.

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:07.070
If you can't stand on your own,
if you can't take a position,

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:09.450
you're never going to
challenge the rules.

00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:11.550
You're not going
to like your life.

00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:13.820
You're not going to
like your partner.

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:15.820
You're not going to
like how you feel.

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:18.470
You will have compromised
your core values.

00:13:18.470 --> 00:13:21.830
You will have sunk below
your own bottom line.

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:23.120
You will be fearful.

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:26.420
You will find yourself spending
years saying things like,

00:13:26.420 --> 00:13:29.810
we're not allowed to do this,
and I'm not allowed to do that.

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:32.570
You're going to feel trapped.

00:13:32.570 --> 00:13:36.000
You are going to
blame your spouse.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.570
If you imagine yourself one
year, five year, 10 years.

00:13:41.570 --> 00:13:43.890
I'm married almost 40 years.

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:46.770
Find yourself all the
way down the line,

00:13:46.770 --> 00:13:49.710
you won't even be able
to recognize yourself.

00:13:49.710 --> 00:13:52.500
You will have turned
yourself into a pretzel

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:57.810
of acceptability, and you
won't be able to stand it.

00:13:57.810 --> 00:14:00.000
Why this is important
is that you have

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.130
to realize what's at stake.

00:14:02.130 --> 00:14:06.090
You've sacrificed
your I for your we.

00:14:06.090 --> 00:14:08.460
And in order to be
happily married,

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:11.070
to be in a satisfying
relationship,

00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:13.860
we have to be as
connected to ourselves

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.890
as we are to our spouse.

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:19.650
If you can't do
that, what's at stake

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:23.670
is your vitality,
your well-being,

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:29.010
and really even possibly
your entire relationship.

00:14:29.010 --> 00:14:32.840
So here's where my
personal story comes in.

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:35.420
I come home from this workshop.

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:39.280
I've gotten this new
idea, and I'm ecstatic.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:42.440
I've finally figured out why
my husband and I are fighting

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:44.370
like a couple of junkyard dogs.

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:46.100
I figure, this is it.

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:46.670
I've got it.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:48.500
So I come home, and
I'm all excited.

00:14:48.500 --> 00:14:52.820
And I say, essentially,
honey, this

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:54.830
is the greatest thing
that's ever happened.

00:14:54.830 --> 00:14:58.070
I'm going to dismantle
our entire marriage right

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:00.183
down to the rafters
and we're going

00:15:00.183 --> 00:15:02.690
to remodel this whole
thing while we live in it,

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:06.440
and I'm going to be the
architect and the carpenter.

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.560
So my husband, you
know, he didn't

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:13.970
embrace all of these ideas with
quite the relish that I did.

00:15:13.970 --> 00:15:17.135
And you know, pretty
much what he said was,

00:15:17.135 --> 00:15:20.860
I pretty much think our
marriage is fine as it is.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:23.470
So that didn't deter me.

00:15:23.470 --> 00:15:24.640
I decided, no.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:25.780
I'm going to keep at it.

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:27.710
I knew that this was right.

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:30.280
You know, but then
actually-- so to be honest,

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:33.460
what he actually said after
I think our marriage is fine

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:37.930
as it is, he actually said,
you went to a workshop

00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:40.540
for the weekend and you
came back brainwashed.

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:43.520
And you are, essentially, you're
not going to save our marriage.

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:46.050
You are about to destroy it.

00:15:46.050 --> 00:15:48.750
So, I mean, I can't blame
him for thinking this.

00:15:48.750 --> 00:15:52.110
I mean, I'm saying things
like, in order to be close,

00:15:52.110 --> 00:15:53.970
we have to be separate.

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:56.870
In order to stop fighting,
we have to disagree.

00:15:56.870 --> 00:15:58.840
You know, these things
don't make any sense,

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:01.870
and so I can understand.

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:03.840
And here's the other thing.

00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:07.200
I was pretty much--
here's the picture.

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:09.270
This is exactly what I was like.

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:11.790
I came home like
a lunatic zealot.

00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:13.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:16.830
I knew that this
was right, but there

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:20.850
was some way in which I couldn't
actually sell it to him.

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:24.345
So I kept trotting out my
good ideas, and books to read,

00:16:24.345 --> 00:16:27.320
and things to do.

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:30.090
And you know, I was like
a door-to-door salesman

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:33.920
trying to sell a reluctant
housewife a new vacuum cleaner.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:35.040
I don't really need this.

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:37.120
Mine works just fine.

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:40.560
So I was about to
give up, and then I

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:46.680
realized that maybe I'm
going about this all wrong.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:51.150
I realized that
the instructions,

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:55.510
what I was going by, was that
you have to stand on your own.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:16:57.520
You have to take risks.

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:00.960
But what I was doing
was exactly the opposite

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:02.670
of what I needed to do.

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:05.880
I was trying to get
my husband's buy in.

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:08.700
It was as if I
was saying, honey,

00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:11.550
I could very well stand
and be separate from you

00:17:11.550 --> 00:17:13.230
if you don't join me.

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:16.930
I can't take the lead
if you don't come along.

00:17:16.930 --> 00:17:21.240
And that was when I realized
that this business of changing

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:25.050
my marriage was going
to be a whole lot harder

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:29.910
and a little more complicated
than I had first anticipated.

00:17:29.910 --> 00:17:34.380
I realized then that if I was
going to change my marriage,

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:36.950
I was going to have
to change it myself.

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:49.880
So I didn't have any real
rules for how to do this,

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:53.520
but these are the
principles that I had.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:56.560
You can't change your partner.

00:17:56.560 --> 00:17:59.320
You have to take risks.

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:02.460
You have to challenge the
rules that confine you

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:05.220
and frustrate you.

00:18:05.220 --> 00:18:08.070
You have to recognize and
accept that this is not

00:18:08.070 --> 00:18:10.740
a kind of a beeline to change.

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:15.420
You're going to have to
learn by falling seven times

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:17.526
and standing up eight.

00:18:17.526 --> 00:18:23.630
And most of all, you're going
to need to focus on yourself.

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:27.890
Well, I decided that
focusing on myself

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:31.500
was the best place to begin.

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:35.790
So instead of focusing on
all of the ways in which he

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:38.340
was contributing to
our difficulties,

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:42.510
when focusing on myself I
discovered a handful of things.

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:44.680
I'm as stubborn as my husband.

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:47.970
I am as likely to
start a fight as he is.

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:51.990
I am maybe even less
likely to allow it to end.

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:56.760
I will be willing to
fight about anything,

00:18:56.760 --> 00:18:59.820
as ridiculous and
stupid as it might be,

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:02.870
as long as I have to
end up being right.

00:19:02.870 --> 00:19:07.870
But the worst thing, the most
painful observation that I had

00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:10.240
was that I realized
that I have the staying

00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:12.640
power of a dandelion.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:15.250
Under pressure, I
would just crumble.

00:19:15.250 --> 00:19:18.550
And it didn't really
match my sense of myself,

00:19:18.550 --> 00:19:20.110
who I am out in the world.

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:23.530
But somehow at home,
there were these ways

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:28.710
that our interactions would,
you know, just make me dissolve.

00:19:28.710 --> 00:19:33.640
So I decided that further than
just this focus, which helped,

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:38.810
I learned how to stop pulling
my end of the tug-of-war rope.

00:19:38.810 --> 00:19:41.060
What I realized
that I needed to do

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:46.580
was I needed to pick this most
frustrating, mind boggling

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:49.370
interaction that I would
have with my husband.

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:52.950
It's what I refer to as
our loopy-logic fight.

00:19:55.630 --> 00:19:59.000
We'd start-- it didn't matter
what we were talking about,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.100
but within a short
period of time,

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:03.905
he's throwing things in
from left field and right.

00:20:03.905 --> 00:20:05.900
And I'd be saying, wait,
wait, wait a minute.

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:07.207
Weren't we talking about shoes?

00:20:07.207 --> 00:20:07.790
Wait a second.

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:09.990
I thought we were
talking about bananas.

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:11.280
What's going on?

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:14.700
And I would just lose
my ability to think.

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:16.010
He was very good.

00:20:16.010 --> 00:20:16.775
I really have to--

00:20:16.775 --> 00:20:18.630
I admire competence.

00:20:18.630 --> 00:20:21.950
He was terrific, but
it would make me lose--

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:24.320
I felt I was losing my mind.

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:29.090
So what I began doing was
experimenting with what would

00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:32.780
it take for me to maintain
my thoughts, to feel

00:20:32.780 --> 00:20:35.670
like I'm staying in one piece?

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:39.770
So I tried deep breathing, and
I tried counting backwards.

00:20:39.770 --> 00:20:43.440
And I tried writing down the
points that I wanted to make.

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:45.290
But none of that worked.

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:50.290
So then one day I decided to
take a physical step back,

00:20:50.290 --> 00:20:53.400
and I noticed I was able to
maintain my thinking better,

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:55.230
but not very well.

00:20:55.230 --> 00:20:57.190
So I took another step back.

00:20:57.190 --> 00:20:58.740
And then I experimented.

00:20:58.740 --> 00:21:01.410
I'd come back in the
room, and I would just

00:21:01.410 --> 00:21:02.880
lose it in about six seconds.

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:04.440
And I'd come back
out of the room.

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:05.520
So I did this--

00:21:05.520 --> 00:21:08.100
honestly, people say,
how long did it take?

00:21:08.100 --> 00:21:10.410
It took a year.

00:21:10.410 --> 00:21:14.160
It took a year
for me to actually

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:17.190
be able to stand there.

00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:18.450
And this is how it happened.

00:21:18.450 --> 00:21:21.870
One day in the middle of
one of our stupid go rounds,

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:25.450
I realized I didn't
have to leave the room.

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:28.410
There I was, and it was
like suddenly his words

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:31.050
were like snowflakes
falling through the air.

00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:34.980
And I was perfectly calm,
and I knew what I thought,

00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:37.560
and I knew what I wanted to say.

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:40.725
And it was like popping
outside of the pull of gravity

00:21:40.725 --> 00:21:45.710
and just floating
free through space.

00:21:45.710 --> 00:21:50.530
And so here's what I'm
going to ask for you to do.

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:52.600
I would like for you--

00:21:52.600 --> 00:21:55.440
here's my question.

00:21:55.440 --> 00:21:59.470
What experience
do you have, what

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:02.750
is it like for you, what
experience do you have

00:22:02.750 --> 00:22:05.050
where you lose yourself?

00:22:05.050 --> 00:22:08.630
Where what you want,
it feels out of reach?

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:13.580
Where what goes on makes your
head spin and frustrate you,

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:17.940
or makes you shut down
or cry, or blow up?

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:22.320
What one situation would
you like to master?

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:28.090
So I'd like you to just take
a minute and write it down.

00:22:28.090 --> 00:22:31.060
One way to think
about it is this.

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:36.850
Instead of X, I want to do
Y. Instead of blowing up,

00:22:36.850 --> 00:22:38.890
I want to remain calm.

00:22:38.890 --> 00:22:42.460
Instead of crying
when I'm angry,

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:46.120
I want to be able to hold
my thoughts together.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:49.230
I want to be able
to express myself.

00:22:49.230 --> 00:22:52.270
Now, in order for
you to do this,

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:56.410
you're going to have
to do two things.

00:22:56.410 --> 00:23:00.520
You're going to have to give up
trying to change your partner,

00:23:00.520 --> 00:23:03.070
and I mean really give it up.

00:23:03.070 --> 00:23:06.880
I don't mean just lip service,
no pun intended there.

00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:10.210
I don't mean lip service to the
idea of secretly believing you

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:12.370
partner should change.

00:23:12.370 --> 00:23:14.650
People come in and they--

00:23:14.650 --> 00:23:16.810
it's like they're bringing
in a broken toaster

00:23:16.810 --> 00:23:18.640
to the fix-it shop in my office.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:20.380
And it's like, here.

00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:23.270
I finally brought-- I'm bringing
my situation to an expert.

00:23:23.270 --> 00:23:26.890
I've tried to fix my
partner, and here it goes.

00:23:26.890 --> 00:23:29.470
And so it's not like that.

00:23:29.470 --> 00:23:32.980
The thing about marriage
is that it's a choice.

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:37.030
We can stay with our
partner, or we can leave.

00:23:37.030 --> 00:23:43.990
But if we're going to stay,
we have one of two choices.

00:23:43.990 --> 00:23:47.860
We can be completely
driven nuts by our partner,

00:23:47.860 --> 00:23:51.580
or we can figure out what we're
going to do with ourselves.

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:58.800
So the other thing you're
going to have to do,

00:23:58.800 --> 00:24:02.580
you're going to have to totally
give up the "it takes two"

00:24:02.580 --> 00:24:03.205
paradigm.

00:24:03.205 --> 00:24:04.580
You're going to
have to throw out

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:09.080
all the stuff about fairness
and needing both partners

00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:11.840
to work as a team and change.

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:14.240
See, this is one of the
things that surprised me

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:20.390
in my own marriage, that as I
was busy focusing on myself,

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:25.440
my husband was actually
changing in ways all on his own.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:26.570
He was calming down.

00:24:26.570 --> 00:24:30.620
And occasionally, he was even
the more levelheaded arguer.

00:24:30.620 --> 00:24:33.416
When we would get
into something, he--

00:24:33.416 --> 00:24:36.680
you know, one day he's
completely surprised me.

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:44.210
I came home to make lunch,
and he left all this stuff

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:46.970
all over the counter,
the plate and the fork

00:24:46.970 --> 00:24:49.020
and all of that stuff.

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:51.770
And I was immediately incensed.

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:55.640
And so we sort of got into it.

00:24:55.640 --> 00:24:58.700
Oh, like, what a nice way for
you to come home and say hello.

00:24:58.700 --> 00:25:00.830
Well, you know, I
only have 15 minutes

00:25:00.830 --> 00:25:02.480
and I have to deal
with your mess.

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:05.120
Back and forth, and
back and forth we went.

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:08.540
And then he stopped
and he said, OK.

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:09.380
Hold on a minute.

00:25:09.380 --> 00:25:11.060
Let's back up.

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:14.480
So in other words, you
come home in a rush

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:16.970
and complain about my mess.

00:25:16.970 --> 00:25:20.070
I get defensive, and
you feel despair.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:21.860
Is that about right?

00:25:21.860 --> 00:25:24.430
And I said, uh, yeah.

00:25:24.430 --> 00:25:27.500
Now, really, I was
about to fall over.

00:25:27.500 --> 00:25:29.660
And he said, yeah.

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:30.680
I can see that.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:32.720
And then he began to clean up.

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:37.490
So what happens when you
stop focusing on your partner

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:40.030
and you focus on yourself--
that was what he did.

00:25:40.030 --> 00:25:44.780
He was focused on me, and then
he was focused on himself.

00:25:44.780 --> 00:25:46.790
So you're going to
have to completely

00:25:46.790 --> 00:25:52.220
give up the two to tango
paradigm in order for this

00:25:52.220 --> 00:25:53.840
to work.

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:57.265
Now, here's the interesting
thing that people say,

00:25:57.265 --> 00:26:03.340
you know, in business, people
are impressed with leadership.

00:26:03.340 --> 00:26:06.550
They call leaders, they
call it being an innovator.

00:26:06.550 --> 00:26:10.630
You know, they say, you
know, you're a trendsetter.

00:26:10.630 --> 00:26:12.910
But when I suggest
that people have

00:26:12.910 --> 00:26:15.790
to take [INAUDIBLE]
in their own marriage,

00:26:15.790 --> 00:26:18.130
they think that I'm
essentially telling them

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:21.970
that they're going to have
to be some sort of doormat.

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:27.130
So I promise you, I'm not asking
you to roll over and play dead,

00:26:27.130 --> 00:26:30.430
or give up on the things
that are important to you,

00:26:30.430 --> 00:26:34.360
or just live with conditions
that you can't stand.

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:38.800
I'm really suggesting
that you recognize

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:43.600
the power of being a leader for
change in your relationship,

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:47.320
and it really is going to
start with that one thing

00:26:47.320 --> 00:26:50.320
that I'm asking you
to look at, the one

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:55.100
thing that you can change, the
one thing that you can control.

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:59.560
And don't be surprised if
it takes a long time for you

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:04.570
to master that that one
thing that I asked you to do.

00:27:04.570 --> 00:27:06.850
It's an incredibly--
it's so much more

00:27:06.850 --> 00:27:12.830
empowering than waiting
for your partner to change.

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:17.080
So you know, and basically
what I want you to understand

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:20.500
is that you have more
power than you think.

00:27:20.500 --> 00:27:23.480
If you're skeptical,
you're not alone.

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:25.210
I mean, really, I'm
asking you to let

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:28.570
go of one of the most cherished
beliefs, that people have

00:27:28.570 --> 00:27:31.480
to change as a
team, that it's not

00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:35.170
worth doing if your
spouse doesn't join you.

00:27:35.170 --> 00:27:39.010
So I'm really just asking
you to take the challenge,

00:27:39.010 --> 00:27:40.780
challenge yourself.

00:27:40.780 --> 00:27:43.990
The goal is not here to turn
you into a little island

00:27:43.990 --> 00:27:46.090
of self-sufficiency.

00:27:46.090 --> 00:27:49.300
It's about turning you
into a partner who's

00:27:49.300 --> 00:27:54.480
capable of change, who's
capable of leadership.

00:27:54.480 --> 00:27:59.410
One person must take the
first step in change.

00:27:59.410 --> 00:28:04.700
My invitation to you is, why
not let that person be you?

00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:09.400
Thank you.

