00:30:28.180 --> 00:30:29.386
can get a night's sleep.

00:30:29.386 --> 00:30:30.010
SPEAKER 1: Yes.

00:30:30.010 --> 00:30:30.310
WINIFRED REILLY: Right?

00:30:30.310 --> 00:30:32.590
SPEAKER 1: And to
self-soothe ourselves,

00:30:32.590 --> 00:30:34.764
as a partner in the marriage.

00:30:34.764 --> 00:30:35.680
WINIFRED REILLY: Yeah.

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:37.510
I mean, if you think
about it, you're

00:30:37.510 --> 00:30:40.540
in the middle of a
thing with your partner.

00:30:40.540 --> 00:30:44.230
If you're relying on
them to be soothing you,

00:30:44.230 --> 00:30:45.670
I mean, they're busy.

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:47.354
Their brain is lit
up at that moment.

00:30:47.354 --> 00:30:48.520
So what are you going to do?

00:30:48.520 --> 00:30:50.370
Go into some sort of free fall?

00:30:50.370 --> 00:30:54.790
I mean, you have to actually
settle down and tell yourself,

00:30:54.790 --> 00:30:56.800
I'm really going to be OK.

00:30:56.800 --> 00:30:59.150
But one of my clients
had a wonderful phrase.

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:01.870
He said that the thing that
would help him the most

00:31:01.870 --> 00:31:05.930
was that when he got anxious
he would remind himself,

00:31:05.930 --> 00:31:07.670
he would say, OK.

00:31:07.670 --> 00:31:10.390
I might get hurt here,
but I'm not going to die.

00:31:10.390 --> 00:31:11.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:11.590 --> 00:31:15.906
That was his self-soothing,
and so we find something.

00:31:15.906 --> 00:31:17.780
SPEAKER 1: What are some
of your suggestions?

00:31:17.780 --> 00:31:18.613
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:31:18.613 --> 00:31:20.890
Well, like I said,
you can breath.

00:31:20.890 --> 00:31:24.640
I think you have to
start with the novel idea

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:27.190
that it's actually your job.

00:31:27.190 --> 00:31:29.700
And I think that's a
big beginning part.

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:33.950
You know, being able to lean on
each other and being together,

00:31:33.950 --> 00:31:38.140
like I said, this is not
about being a little island.

00:31:38.140 --> 00:31:42.440
It's just about-- it's nice to
be able to lean on each other,

00:31:42.440 --> 00:31:45.100
but you have to be able
to stand on your feet,

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:47.320
especially when
you're not agreeing.

00:31:47.320 --> 00:31:49.410
You know, you can't
lean on somebody else

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:53.110
while they're agitated or
holding their position.

00:31:53.110 --> 00:31:55.060
So you can breathe.

00:31:55.060 --> 00:31:57.430
You can talk yourself down.

00:31:57.430 --> 00:31:58.900
You can take breaks.

00:31:58.900 --> 00:32:01.210
You can say, hold on.

00:32:01.210 --> 00:32:02.364
I'm just getting flooded.

00:32:02.364 --> 00:32:03.280
I'm going to step out.

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:07.960
I'm not suggesting that you, you
know, come back two days later.

00:32:07.960 --> 00:32:09.520
I'm saying, just five minutes.

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:10.840
Quiet your brain down.

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:13.552
So it really is an experiment.

00:32:13.552 --> 00:32:15.010
Sometimes there
are issues that are

00:32:15.010 --> 00:32:17.980
so hot to deal with that
you pick them up tomorrow.

00:32:17.980 --> 00:32:20.010
SPEAKER 1: Mhm.

00:32:20.010 --> 00:32:22.370
That's great.

00:32:22.370 --> 00:32:26.630
Did you want to ask a question?

00:32:26.630 --> 00:32:28.600
And have Dory's
questions right here.

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:29.433
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:32:32.551 --> 00:32:34.550
SPEAKER 1: I'm going to
read the Dory questions,

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:39.990
and feel free to add as
