00:32:39.990 --> 00:32:43.120
And it is anonymous.

00:32:43.120 --> 00:32:45.310
So the first
question we have is,

00:32:45.310 --> 00:32:50.070
how to convince your partner
to go to couples therapy,

00:32:50.070 --> 00:32:51.872
and is it helpful
to do it alone?

00:32:51.872 --> 00:32:52.830
WINIFRED REILLY: Great.

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:54.720
I love that question.

00:32:54.720 --> 00:32:57.480
You can't convince
or persuade someone

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:00.060
to do something that
they're uncomfortable with.

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:03.490
You can ask, and it's
actually your job to ask.

00:33:03.490 --> 00:33:07.930
I mean, nobody is going to
advocate for you except you.

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:09.910
But you know, there are
reasons people don't

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:11.610
want to go to couple's therapy.

00:33:11.610 --> 00:33:14.710
They think it's a first
step toward divorce.

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:16.060
They're fearful.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:20.750
They think that things
are fine as they are.

00:33:20.750 --> 00:33:23.800
Let's, you know,
don't rock the boat.

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:27.650
Or, you know, they just
don't believe in it.

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:30.880
And so it's "The One
to Tango" principle.

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:34.317
If there's something important
to you, go on your own.

00:33:34.317 --> 00:33:34.900
Take the lead.

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:37.480
I do work with some
people by themselves

00:33:37.480 --> 00:33:41.620
without their partner, and
so a good couples therapist

00:33:41.620 --> 00:33:44.931
will actually help you,
not just take your side.

00:33:44.931 --> 00:33:45.930
That's not that helpful.

00:33:45.930 --> 00:33:48.190
I mean, it's lovely,
but if you're

00:33:48.190 --> 00:33:51.280
talking about nonsense
in your relationship,

00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:54.310
you actually have to have
somebody who can, you know,

00:33:54.310 --> 00:33:57.360
not just commiserate with
you, but actually help

00:33:57.360 --> 00:33:59.710
you take charge of yourself.

00:33:59.710 --> 00:34:04.360
So you know, I think
sometimes what people--

00:34:04.360 --> 00:34:08.469
it sort of seems obvious.

00:34:08.469 --> 00:34:13.409
You can start by saying, this
is really important to me

00:34:13.409 --> 00:34:15.300
and I'd like you to go.

00:34:15.300 --> 00:34:16.560
At least try it once.

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:21.300
But really, go by yourself.

00:34:21.300 --> 00:34:22.389
Go by yourself.

00:34:22.389 --> 00:34:25.780
A lot can happen, if you don't
just go there to complain,

00:34:25.780 --> 00:34:27.429
but you go there to say--

00:34:27.429 --> 00:34:30.040
like I did-- you
know, say, oh, wait.

00:34:30.040 --> 00:34:31.610
I'm as big of a hothead.

00:34:31.610 --> 00:34:34.239
Oh, here's my contribution
to the difficulty,

00:34:34.239 --> 00:34:37.359
and I want help with that.

00:34:37.359 --> 00:34:38.830
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:34:38.830 --> 00:34:40.960
What are some of
the steps one can

00:34:40.960 --> 00:34:44.860
take when they're screaming,
name calling, as well

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:47.770
as verbal abuse in their
relationship but the partner

00:34:47.770 --> 00:34:51.790
refuses to stop this
behavior, or the partner says

00:34:51.790 --> 00:34:54.589
it will stop if the
partner does such and such?

00:34:54.589 --> 00:34:55.880
WINIFRED REILLY: If you change.

00:34:55.880 --> 00:34:56.270
SPEAKER 1: Yes.

00:34:56.270 --> 00:34:56.807
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:56.807 --> 00:34:57.640
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:34:57.640 --> 00:34:58.306
Well, all right.

00:34:58.306 --> 00:35:00.970
So if somebody is
screaming and yelling,

00:35:00.970 --> 00:35:03.960
I differentiate this from,
you know, where there's, like,

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:04.780
physical violence.

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:07.690
So let's just take
that off of the table.

00:35:07.690 --> 00:35:11.890
It's just kind of
bedlam at your house.

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:14.830
I think the surprising
thing is for you

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:16.810
to be able to remain calm.

00:35:16.810 --> 00:35:19.640
I learned this from my
son's kindergarten teacher.

00:35:19.640 --> 00:35:24.390
The room would be chaotic,
and she would lower her voice.

00:35:24.390 --> 00:35:27.670
She would get really quiet,
and the energy in the room

00:35:27.670 --> 00:35:28.900
would change.

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:32.920
Now, if your spouse
is off the rails,

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:36.510
you're not going to be able to
reason with him or her anyway.

00:35:36.510 --> 00:35:40.560
And so I suggest you sit
down and be a witness.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.792
Also you don't have to
argue every single point.

00:35:43.792 --> 00:35:46.000
I mean, you know, you don't
have to argue if somebody

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:47.395
is saying the Earth is flat.

00:35:47.395 --> 00:35:48.025
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:48.025 --> 00:35:50.780
You don't actually have to
say, well, actually, here.

00:35:50.780 --> 00:35:52.480
Here is why it's round.

00:35:52.480 --> 00:35:55.120
You have to calm down.

00:35:55.120 --> 00:36:02.440
You also might want to try with
a really nasty spouse saying,

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:06.670
you know, do you actually
think I can hear you

00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:08.560
when you talk like that?

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:10.240
How about if we sit down.

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:13.180
Why don't you tell me what it
is you want me to understand,

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:16.780
or I don't really have any
idea why you get so frustrated.

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:20.380
Do you have any idea
why you totally lose it?

00:36:20.380 --> 00:36:22.060
You know, that you
start to become

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:26.119
the ambassador for sanity
in a crazy situation.

00:36:26.119 --> 00:36:27.160
At least, that's a start.

00:36:30.060 --> 00:36:32.120
SPEAKER 1: Next
question, you talked

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:36.770
about standing on your
own and taking a position.

00:36:36.770 --> 00:36:39.980
In the same vein, do you think
it's absolutely necessary

00:36:39.980 --> 00:36:44.630
to spend time alone explicitly,
be single for many years

00:36:44.630 --> 00:36:46.930
before being married?

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:49.770
WINIFRED REILLY: Well, I wasn't.

00:36:49.770 --> 00:36:53.190
And you know, I was very
young when I got married.

00:36:53.190 --> 00:36:56.840
And my sense of self, oh, I
sure thought I was an adult,

00:36:56.840 --> 00:37:00.210
but I had lots of growing to do.

00:37:00.210 --> 00:37:05.620
I think that coming in at
any phase in your life,

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:07.500
you're still going
to meet challenges.

00:37:07.500 --> 00:37:10.470
That whole list of why is
marriage hard that I talked

00:37:10.470 --> 00:37:14.460
about in the beginning, it's
still going to be difficult.

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:16.695
You know, you're going
to think, oh, I'm

00:37:16.695 --> 00:37:18.700
a really sane,
well-adjusted person.

00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:21.060
I can handle just
about anything.

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:24.480
And then, you know, you yourself
in a small space with somebody

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:30.732
and you're going to just see all
the little holes in yourself.

00:37:30.732 --> 00:37:31.940
You know, there's this quote.

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:34.660
"A man can be a fool
and not know it,

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:36.300
but not if he's married."

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:36.800
You know.

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:37.300
SPEAKER 1: Very true.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:39.030
WINIFRED REILLY: A
woman can be a fool

00:37:39.030 --> 00:37:41.220
and not know it,
unless she's married.

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:47.100
And so I think that the
more solid and strong

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:49.890
we are as people,
the better it is.

00:37:49.890 --> 00:37:51.835
But you're still going
to hit the trenches.

00:37:51.835 --> 00:37:53.520
You're still going
to have to learn

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:58.830
how you live with this person
when agreeing to disagree

00:37:58.830 --> 00:38:02.820
does not solve every problem.

00:38:02.820 --> 00:38:06.600
SPEAKER 1: This next
question is great.

00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:09.240
Any advice for
single people trying

00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:12.030
to find or choose a
partner and wanting

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:14.324
to make that relationship work?

00:38:14.324 --> 00:38:15.240
WINIFRED REILLY: Yeah.

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:20.610
Well, you know, it's the same as
anyone even in a relationship.

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:25.260
Be clear about what you want,
know as much about yourself,

00:38:25.260 --> 00:38:26.850
and be willing to be brave.

00:38:26.850 --> 00:38:28.460
Be willing to reveal yourself.

00:38:28.460 --> 00:38:34.290
I have clients who come in
20, 30 years down the line,

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:37.290
and they've hidden so
many parts of themselves

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:40.170
that they feel strangled.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:43.680
And you know, so the
thing when you're

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:49.890
looking for a relationship,
find somebody who's curious.

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:52.780
Find somebody who wants
to take an adventure,

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:55.140
but isn't going to be
a lark with anyone.

00:38:55.140 --> 00:38:57.510
It's just not going to
be a walk in the park,

00:38:57.510 --> 00:39:05.640
but somebody who is willing
to laugh, explore, grow.

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:10.670
It helps.

00:39:10.670 --> 00:39:11.900
SPEAKER 1: And it's--

00:39:11.900 --> 00:39:14.524
I appreciate what you said
just about knowing yourself.

00:39:14.524 --> 00:39:15.440
WINIFRED REILLY: Yeah.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:20.190
SPEAKER 1: Because it
seems like no matter what,

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:26.280
how much you investigate
the person, or interview

00:39:26.280 --> 00:39:28.292
the person, or try to
analyze the person.

00:39:28.292 --> 00:39:29.250
WINIFRED REILLY: Right.

00:39:29.250 --> 00:39:30.900
SPEAKER 1: It always
comes down to who

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:32.360
you are on the other side.

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:32.463
WINIFRED REILLY: Yes.

00:39:32.463 --> 00:39:33.129
And that's true.

00:39:33.129 --> 00:39:36.240
I mean, it really is--

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:40.680
you know, if you don't know
what you want, and who you are,

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:42.900
and what you think, if
you have no connection

00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:45.780
to your inner most
reliable witness,

00:39:45.780 --> 00:39:48.180
you're just going
to be moving about

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:50.520
and you're not
going to actually be

00:39:50.520 --> 00:39:54.880
able to have your relationship
go in any direction.

00:39:54.880 --> 00:39:56.615
And so, you know,
it's not for sissies,

00:39:56.615 --> 00:39:59.965
is what say people say about
long-term relationships.

00:39:59.965 --> 00:40:00.840
SPEAKER 1: Very true.

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:02.760
And this one, this
question, is about

00:40:02.760 --> 00:40:04.110
long-distance relationships.

00:40:04.110 --> 00:40:05.070
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:06.445
SPEAKER 1: How
would one approach

00:40:06.445 --> 00:40:09.810
this when a couple is in a
long-distance relationship?

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.060
And what are your
thoughts on each partner

00:40:12.060 --> 00:40:14.964
seeing a separate therapist?

00:40:14.964 --> 00:40:16.380
WINIFRED REILLY:
You know, so this

00:40:16.380 --> 00:40:19.200
may sound like a kind
of a jokey answer,

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:21.990
but therapy can be one
of the worst things you

00:40:21.990 --> 00:40:23.370
could do for your marriage.

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:25.380
I mean, there's
statistics about it.

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:27.630
So it doesn't mean don't do it.

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:30.660
It's just that you
will sometimes--

00:40:30.660 --> 00:40:33.690
therapists will take sides.

00:40:33.690 --> 00:40:35.580
You know, you've got two people.

00:40:35.580 --> 00:40:39.630
If you're focusing, if you're
doing relationship work,

00:40:39.630 --> 00:40:40.704
not just inner work.

00:40:40.704 --> 00:40:42.870
Inner work is a different
thing when you're doing it

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:44.040
within individual therapy.

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:46.110
When you're doing
relationship work--

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:49.320
I've actually worked with
people where someone flies in

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:52.800
and I see them for, you know,
two or three hours, and maybe

00:40:52.800 --> 00:40:55.140
a couple of times
in a short time.

00:40:55.140 --> 00:40:59.190
And then they go back and
they do their own work.

00:40:59.190 --> 00:41:02.250
But in a long-distance
relationship,

00:41:02.250 --> 00:41:04.060
some of the pressure
is off, you know?

00:41:04.060 --> 00:41:07.200
In the beginning I showed this
cartoon with the definition

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:09.180
of marriage is two
people in a rowboat,

00:41:09.180 --> 00:41:11.342
and they're rolling in
opposite directions.

00:41:11.342 --> 00:41:13.050
But that's some of
the stuff that happens

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:15.220
when you're living together.

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:17.280
Things heat up.

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.080
But you know, it's
the same, I suppose.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:24.870
You know, any work, any
time that you're together,

00:41:24.870 --> 00:41:27.510
pay attention to
yourself, what you want.

00:41:27.510 --> 00:41:32.290
You know, don't shy away
from challenging things.

00:41:32.290 --> 00:41:35.080
SPEAKER 1: When you mentioned
that therapy isn't necessarily

00:41:35.080 --> 00:41:38.190
the best thing, it reminded me
of what you told us at lunch,

00:41:38.190 --> 00:41:40.750
that you had a therapist that
recommended something that

00:41:40.750 --> 00:41:40.990
wasn't--

00:41:40.990 --> 00:41:41.560
WINIFRED REILLY: Yeah, yeah.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:43.660
My therapist said, oh,
your husband, you know,

00:41:43.660 --> 00:41:44.870
you're so frustrated.

00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:49.240
He's really never going to
really take a hold and grow.

00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:51.970
You really should, you
know, just move on,

00:41:51.970 --> 00:41:53.380
which was stunning.

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:57.400
And I actually stopped that
therapy pretty quickly,

00:41:57.400 --> 00:42:02.830
realizing that I would have much
rather somebody said, you know,

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:04.930
what I'm saying to people.

00:42:04.930 --> 00:42:07.270
Well, this is
challenging, you know?

00:42:07.270 --> 00:42:08.630
Fasten your seat belts.

00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:10.360
Put on your work boots.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:10.900
Get going.

00:42:10.900 --> 00:42:11.775
See where you can go.

00:42:11.775 --> 00:42:15.870
It wasn't that my husband
was immune to change,

00:42:15.870 --> 00:42:20.080
he just was kind of more content
with things as they were.

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:25.160
So I came in with these ideas
for how to have it go better,

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:29.020
and you know, and
at this point, he

00:42:29.020 --> 00:42:31.570
wouldn't argue that
our relationship is

00:42:31.570 --> 00:42:35.984
much, much better because
we both basically grew up.

00:42:35.984 --> 00:42:37.900
SPEAKER 1: And that leads
me to a question of,

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:40.540
how does one choose a therapist?

00:42:40.540 --> 00:42:45.612
Because if you have a therapist
that is quick to say, yeah.

00:42:45.612 --> 00:42:46.570
This isn't working out.

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:48.220
You guys should
just get divorced.

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:50.470
WINIFRED REILLY: I don't
think you should allow anyone

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:51.850
to tell you to get divorced.

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:52.600
SPEAKER 1: Mhm.

00:42:52.600 --> 00:42:54.766
WINIFRED REILLY: Remember
what I said about marriage

00:42:54.766 --> 00:42:55.900
being a choice.

00:42:55.900 --> 00:43:00.130
You can stay with this
partner or you can leave.

00:43:00.130 --> 00:43:04.210
But if you're going to
stay, you have two choices.

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:07.990
You can figure out what you're
going to do with yourself,

00:43:07.990 --> 00:43:11.680
or you can allow that person
to drive you completely nuts.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:15.520
And this business of figuring
out what to do with yourself

00:43:15.520 --> 00:43:18.487
is really pretty extraordinary.

00:43:18.487 --> 00:43:19.570
There are a lot of things.

00:43:19.570 --> 00:43:23.320
You know, it's not
just we calm down.

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:25.720
But later in the
book, I have a thing

00:43:25.720 --> 00:43:30.010
about what some people
discover to be change.

00:43:30.010 --> 00:43:32.650
Like, one person
said his wife is just

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:37.056
a busy person moving around,
always drove him really crazy.

00:43:37.056 --> 00:43:38.680
And then you realize,
it's a little bit

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:42.310
like living near train
tracks, but people eventually

00:43:42.310 --> 00:43:44.290
stop hearing the train.

00:43:44.290 --> 00:43:46.480
And he just stopped
focusing on it.

00:43:46.480 --> 00:43:48.400
She was always running
around and doing stuff.

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:50.560
He figured out how to
regulate his own state

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:53.260
and be peaceful in the
midst of all of her people

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:54.400
coming and going.

00:43:54.400 --> 00:43:58.810
You know, so rather than,
you need to slow down,

00:43:58.810 --> 00:44:01.840
he figured out how
to just maintain

00:44:01.840 --> 00:44:03.170
his own shape in the context.

00:44:06.109 --> 00:44:07.150
SPEAKER 1: Next question.

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:14.110
How to agree or disagree
on parenting issues,

00:44:14.110 --> 00:44:16.120
how we approach parenting,
if we are coming

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:17.800
from very different places.

00:44:17.800 --> 00:44:19.630
WINIFRED REILLY:
This one, you know,

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:21.520
I could write an entire book.

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:24.580
This one is not a quick
answer because it's

00:44:24.580 --> 00:44:28.090
one of those things that you
can't have two philosophies.

00:44:28.090 --> 00:44:30.550
You can't say, we're never
going to spank the kids

00:44:30.550 --> 00:44:32.220
and somebody is going
to spank the kids,

00:44:32.220 --> 00:44:35.780
or you're never going to do time
out, or you're going to do--

00:44:35.780 --> 00:44:36.280
you know?

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:41.890
And so I can't actually give
this one a quick answer,

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:45.040
but it actually
comes down to needing

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:50.200
to collaborate in some
way, but more to be

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:54.370
persuasive in terms of--

00:44:54.370 --> 00:44:55.240
see, OK.

00:44:55.240 --> 00:44:57.760
When you have two
things and you're only

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:00.610
going to have one
outcome, the only way

00:45:00.610 --> 00:45:03.430
you're going to get
anywhere is that somebody

00:45:03.430 --> 00:45:05.140
is going to have to yield.

00:45:05.140 --> 00:45:07.570
Somebody is going to
have to be generous.

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:09.850
They're going to have
to say, all right.

00:45:09.850 --> 00:45:14.990
This is not my first choice, but
from a solid and strong place,

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:17.110
we'll do what you want.

00:45:17.110 --> 00:45:18.430
We can't compromise.

00:45:18.430 --> 00:45:21.700
You can't have half a time out.

00:45:21.700 --> 00:45:25.480
You can't have one
parent saying we

00:45:25.480 --> 00:45:27.580
have no sugar in the
house and the other one,

00:45:27.580 --> 00:45:30.600
you know, feeding the kid
sugar, or screen time.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:32.880
I mean, these
issues, you have to--

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:34.720
it's sort of like this.

00:45:34.720 --> 00:45:36.400
You're going to
either move over here,

00:45:36.400 --> 00:45:37.858
or you're going to
move over there.

00:45:37.858 --> 00:45:41.950
And how do you do it, I think
it requires a sense of self.

00:45:41.950 --> 00:45:45.370
Don't expect these
conversations to happen quickly.

00:45:45.370 --> 00:45:46.930
Hang in there with it.

00:45:46.930 --> 00:45:50.830
See if you can both come from
the most curious and generous

00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:51.655
places in yourself.

00:45:54.332 --> 00:45:55.206
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:45:55.206 --> 00:45:57.780
And there are a
couple more here.

00:45:57.780 --> 00:46:01.860
How amplified is the
"It Takes One to Tango"

00:46:01.860 --> 00:46:05.760
message when one of the
partners can't change much?

00:46:05.760 --> 00:46:07.430
For example, Asperger's.

00:46:07.507 --> 00:46:08.340
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:10.380
So I do work with
couples like that,

00:46:10.380 --> 00:46:19.680
and so here's the piece that if
the Asperger's person actually

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:25.140
recognizes that there may be
ways that he or she isn't going

00:46:25.140 --> 00:46:29.370
to change, but can acknowledge
that it drives their spouse

00:46:29.370 --> 00:46:31.590
nuts, that's one thing.

00:46:31.590 --> 00:46:33.870
And then for the other
spouse, to give up

00:46:33.870 --> 00:46:37.860
all hope of this
person being different

00:46:37.860 --> 00:46:44.190
and to make your own moves,
and think your own thoughts.

00:46:44.190 --> 00:46:47.580
You know, I work
with one couple where

00:46:47.580 --> 00:46:52.680
the guy would be-- he
would begin every answer,

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:56.820
or every piece of a conversation
was begun with the word no.

00:46:56.820 --> 00:46:58.740
And he eventually stopped.

00:46:58.740 --> 00:47:01.230
She'd say, I'd like
to go to the moon.

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:02.250
And he'd say, no.

00:47:02.250 --> 00:47:04.175
I think, you know,
Pluto would be better.

00:47:04.175 --> 00:47:05.550
But every-- no
was the beginning.

00:47:05.550 --> 00:47:09.810
So she eventually got to,
I can just ignore that word

00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:11.110
and I can listen.

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:13.440
And he actually did change.

00:47:13.440 --> 00:47:16.030
I think people actually
can change, probably

00:47:16.030 --> 00:47:19.950
not everything, but I don't
put a ceiling over what's

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:21.790
possible for people.

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:24.180
But I think, you know,
you pick this person.

00:47:24.180 --> 00:47:27.150
You know somewhat of
what you're getting

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:28.627
and what you're not getting.

00:47:28.627 --> 00:47:30.210
And you have to
figure out how to make

00:47:30.210 --> 00:47:32.859
yourself happy in that context.

00:47:32.859 --> 00:47:34.650
SPEAKER 1: Have you
ever seen the technique

00:47:34.650 --> 00:47:38.550
you described work on a marriage
that has already failed,

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:42.600
where the partners are
divorced or separated?

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:46.025
At which point would you
recommend, as a professional

00:47:46.025 --> 00:47:47.657
with experience, giving up?

00:47:47.657 --> 00:47:48.490
WINIFRED REILLY: OK.

00:47:48.490 --> 00:47:50.865
Well, if it's already failed
and you're already divorced,

00:47:50.865 --> 00:47:52.350
I mean, I have seen
people remarry,

00:47:52.350 --> 00:47:54.433
but I don't think that's
quite what you're asking.

00:47:54.433 --> 00:47:57.180
So I'm going to answer
a question of, like,

00:47:57.180 --> 00:48:00.540
how far gone is too far gone.

00:48:00.540 --> 00:48:04.080
I actually-- you know, my
book opens with this quote.

00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:06.840
It's a Turkish proverb
that says, "No matter

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:09.690
how far you have gone
down the wrong road,

00:48:09.690 --> 00:48:11.670
you can turn around."

00:48:11.670 --> 00:48:13.860
So I never give up.

00:48:13.860 --> 00:48:16.770
It's not my job to tell
people, you know, you can do it

00:48:16.770 --> 00:48:17.790
or you can't do it.

00:48:17.790 --> 00:48:18.990
But I never give up.

00:48:18.990 --> 00:48:22.810
I never put a ceiling over
what's possible for people.

00:48:22.810 --> 00:48:25.060
But here's the thing.

00:48:25.060 --> 00:48:27.460
Marriage is a choice.

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.340
If you want to try
and make it a go,

00:48:30.340 --> 00:48:32.860
I say, you don't have
anything to lose.

00:48:32.860 --> 00:48:34.210
Give it your all.

00:48:34.210 --> 00:48:35.080
See what happens.

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:38.540
There's no guarantee as
to how it will come out.

00:48:38.540 --> 00:48:41.140
But if you have even
one shred of hope,

00:48:41.140 --> 00:48:46.090
start working on your side
of it and don't give up.

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:48.250
You still might
not end up married,

00:48:48.250 --> 00:48:50.590
but I like people
to at least come out

00:48:50.590 --> 00:48:53.080
of it being able
to say, you know,

00:48:53.080 --> 00:48:57.510
I feel as if I really
did everything I could.

00:48:57.510 --> 00:48:59.160
SPEAKER 1: This is
our last question.

00:48:59.160 --> 00:49:06.840
You mentioned giving up the
idea about 50/50 fairness

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:07.920
and working as a team.

00:49:10.540 --> 00:49:12.720
How do you then balance
day-to-day obligations,

00:49:12.720 --> 00:49:16.250
such as parenting, working
without being completely run

00:49:16.250 --> 00:49:18.270
down or bearing
most of the weight?

00:49:18.270 --> 00:49:19.811
WINIFRED REILLY:
Well, you know, it's

00:49:19.811 --> 00:49:22.845
tricky because this is a
common concern, especially

00:49:22.845 --> 00:49:24.720
for the person who feels
like they're already

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:26.310
carrying more weight.

00:49:30.630 --> 00:49:32.940
This idea is not
about how you should

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:36.120
be doing all of the cleaning,
and watching all the kids,

00:49:36.120 --> 00:49:40.620
and turning cartwheels
about everything.

00:49:40.620 --> 00:49:43.530
It really is about-- so if
you're in a situation where

00:49:43.530 --> 00:49:46.310
your partner is not doing much.

00:49:46.310 --> 00:49:48.240
This is a time where
you actually might

00:49:48.240 --> 00:49:50.490
need to really step forward.

00:49:50.490 --> 00:49:55.230
And instead of saying, you know,
like, what's wrong with you,

00:49:55.230 --> 00:49:57.030
you might say--

00:49:57.030 --> 00:50:00.750
this would be like what I would
say to somebody in my office--

00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:02.880
so what do you tell
yourself while you're

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:05.820
sitting there reading
and your wife is running

00:50:05.820 --> 00:50:08.530
around doing the dishes,
unloading the dishwasher,

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:10.950
and juggling three children.

00:50:10.950 --> 00:50:14.110
Like, tell me how that
makes sense to you.

00:50:14.110 --> 00:50:17.370
And so you want to find
yourself in a position

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:20.310
where you're not working
on changing your spouse,

00:50:20.310 --> 00:50:24.720
but that doesn't mean, you know,
blooming where you planted.

00:50:24.720 --> 00:50:27.030
This is why I say it's
going to take gumption.

00:50:27.030 --> 00:50:30.180
You're going to have to move
toward your difficulties

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:32.160
and talk about them in
ways that figure out

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:35.580
ways to talk about them that
are effective, that aren't

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:39.870
about changing the other person
but are really about coming

00:50:39.870 --> 00:50:42.650
forward and being yourself.

00:50:42.650 --> 00:50:43.650
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:50:43.650 --> 00:50:44.886
Thank you so much for coming.

00:50:44.886 --> 00:50:47.150
WINIFRED REILLY: Oh, It's
been really a pleasure.

